desc: Based on its location in Kraków (one of Poland’s top‐performing economic centers) and the qualitative benchmarks provided ulica Na Zakolu Wisły 10 in Podgórze Kraków should be classified as: Very High
Based on its location in the Kraków‐metropolitan periphery (Krakowski powiat in Małopolskie) – a wealthy highly commuter‐integrated district – Ostrężnica would fall into the “High” class.

Based on its location—a small‐town gmina in the more industrial (but still peripheral) northern part of Silesia—and by analogy with the Częstochowa (Medium) benchmark rather than the rural “Low” cases Koszęcin’s district GDP class is:

Answer: Medium.

Based on its location in the largely rural Piła (Pilski) county of Wielkopolskie – a mid-ranking district in a relatively well‐off voivodeship but without the scale of larger urban centres – the most fitting GDP class is:

Answer: Medium

Based on its rural character but located in the relatively prosperous Wielkopolskie province (in the commuter‐belt of Poznań) Kotusz (Grodziski powiat) would be expected to sit just above the national mid-range.  
Answer: Medium

Based on its location in Szamotulski County (Wielkopolskie) – a moderately affluent area on Poznań’s periphery where county‐level GDP outperforms the national average but doesn’t reach the capitals’ levels – I would classify Chojno Wronki as High.

Based on its location—a small town/village in Drawsko County (a relatively rural part of Zachodniopomorskie Voivodeship) comparable to other low-output Polish districts—the most appropriate class for Konotop Drawsko Pomorskie is: Low.
Based on its rural character modest population and distance from the main regional hub (Wrocław) Lwówecki district’s total GDP would fall into the “Low” class.
Based on its profile – a small‐town/rural mountainous district outside major economic centers – Kłodzki (Wolibórz Nowa Ruda) best fits the “Low” class.

Based on its location in the Opole‐Ozimek powiat – a small industrial district on the outskirts of the regional capital Opole – its overall economic output would place it in the middle of our five‐point scale.  

Answer: Medium

Based on its location in the Żniński district of the Kujawsko-Pomorskie voivodeship—which overall posts GDP per capita slightly below Poland’s average and given that Barcin itself is a modest‐sized industrial town near the Bydgoszcz–Toruń growth axis—I would classify its district‐level GDP as Medium.
Based on its location—a small village in a relatively low-GDP primarily rural county of the Warmińsko-mazurskie region—the most appropriate class is: Low.

Based on its location in the Lublin metro‐area (Lubelskie) – a province that overall leans low but whose immediate hinterland around the city of Lublin reaches middle‐range output – Jakubowice Murowane would be classified as:  
Medium
Based on its location in a predominantly rural lower‐income part of Podkarpackie (Gmina Laszki Jarosławski powiat) the appropriate five‐class GDP category is: Low.

Based on its location in the generally less‐affluent Podkarpackie Voivodeship and the fact that Rzeszowski is a suburban/rural district around – but excluding – the city of Rzeszów (whose GDP is booked separately) its per‐district output would fall into the “Low” bracket.  
Answer: Low

Based on its population size (≈120 000) and the strong industrial base in Mielec (a major special economic/aviation zone) – which puts its total district output roughly on par with other “High”‐rated counties like Piotrkowski – the Powiat Mielecki (Otałęż Gmina Czermin) falls into the “High” GDP class.
Based on its location in rural Podlaskie (a lower‐GDP voivodeship) and similarity to other small‐village entries (e.g. Niwiski Czołki) Studzianki would be classified as Low.

Based on its location in the Košice region—which while Slovakia’s second‐largest city area sits below the Bratislava region’s GDP but above the poorer eastern regions—Južné Mesto (Košice IV) falls into the Medium class.

Based on its location in the affluent Praha-západ district of the Central Bohemian (Středočeský) Region – one of the Czech Republic’s highest-output areas due to its close ties to Prague – the most appropriate class is:

Answer: Very High

Based on the fact that Lukov lies in the Ústecký kraj – one of the less affluent heavy‐industry–dominated regions of the Czech Republic with GDP per head well below the national average and total regional output (~€18 billion) in the lower mid‐range – we would classify its regional GDP as: Low.
Based on Vysočina’s total output (roughly €9–10 billion) and its position in the Czech regional ranking (squarely in the mid‐range of the 14 regions) it falls into the “Medium” band.
Based on its location in the Moravskoslezský kraj – one of the Czech Republic’s top‐GDP regions (roughly €18–20 billion) – it clearly falls into the “Very High” class.

Based on its location in Győr-Moson-Sopron – one of Hungary’s top‐3 GDP-producing counties thanks to the Audi plant in Győr and strong cross-border trade with Austria and Slovakia – I would classify its regional GDP as Very High.

Based on Vas county’s position in Western Transdanubia—above the national average but not among Hungary’s very top‐performing counties—the appropriate qualitative class for Sorkifalud (Szombathelyi járás Vas) is:

Answer: Medium

Based on Somogy’s position as one of Hungary’s less‐developed largely rural counties (outside the Budapest–Pest core and the few high-GDP western counties) and its GDP‐per-capita figures sitting well below the national average it fits the “Low” bracket.  
Answer: Low
Based on its county (Borsod-Abaúj-Zemplén) which ranks among Hungary’s less-developed areas alongside Szabolcs-Szatmár-Bereg Szikszó would be classified as Low.

Based on Nógrád county’s position as one of Hungary’s lowest‐GDP regions—comparable to Szabolcs‐Szatmár‐Bereg which was classed “Low”—the appropriate category here is:

Answer: Low

Based on its location in Bács-Kiskun – a largely agricultural mid-to-lower-ranked Hungarian county with total GDP on the order of 3–5 billion € and by analogy with Baktalórántháza (Low) in the similarly underperforming Szabolcs-Szatmár-Bereg Soltvadkert’s wider county falls into the “Low” category.  

Answer: Low
